The contract every module follows. Each module file exports exactly three functions:

js
// modules/leads/leads.js
export function mount(rootEl, ctx) { /* render into rootEl, attach listeners */ }
export function unmount() { /* remove listeners, cancel timers */ }
export const meta = { id: 'leads', label: { de: 'Leads', en: 'Leads' } };
ctx is the only thing the module gets from the outside. It contains state (read), dispatch (write), t (translate), bus (subscribe to events). No global access. If a module wants leads data, it calls ctx.state.leads. If it changes a lead, it calls ctx.dispatch('leads.update', {...}). This is the contract, and it's what makes the puzzle work.

The failure-isolation trick. Your loader.js looks roughly like this:

js
async function loadModule(name, rootEl, ctx) {
  try {
    const m = await import(`../modules/${name}/${name}.js`);
    m.mount(rootEl, ctx);
    return m;
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(`Module ${name} failed:`, err);
    rootEl.innerHTML = `
      <div class="module-error">
        <h3>${ctx.t('module_failed')}: ${name}</h3>
        <p>${err.message}</p>
        <button onclick="location.reload()">Reload</button>
      </div>`;
    ctx.bus.emit('module.failed', { name, err });
    return null;
  }
}
Result: a typo in analytics.js shows a red "Analytics failed" card in that one panel, and Builder, Leads, and Tasks keep working. That is the "one piece breaks, the rest still runs" behavior you described.

